4 There stands Minos horribly, and snarls:
5 he examines the sins at the entrance;
6 he judges and sends according as he entwines himself.

7 I say that when the ill-born soul
8 comes before him, it confesses everything;
9 and that discerner of sins

10 sees what place in hell is for it;
11 he lashes himself with his tail as many times
12 as the degrees he wants it to be cast down.

19 "see how you enter and in whom you trust;
20 do not let the wideness of the entrance deceive you!"
21 And my leader to him: "Why do you keep shouting?

31 The infernal storm, which never rests,
32 drives the spirits with its power;
33 whirling and smiting, it torments them.

34 When they arrive before the ruin,
35 there are the shrieks, the weeping, the lament;
36 there they blaspheme the divine power.

43 here, there, down, up;
44 no hope ever comforts them,
45 not only of rest, but of lesser pain.

49 shades borne by the said storm;
50 wherefore I said: "Master, who are those
51 people whom the black air so chastises?"

61 The next is she who killed herself for love,
62 and broke faith with the ashes of Sichaeus;
63 then comes the lustful Cleopatra.

82 As doves, called by desire,
83 with wings lifted and steady to the sweet nest
84 come through the air, borne by their will;

127 One day, for delight, we were reading
128 of Lancelot, how love constrained him;
129 we were alone and without any suspicion.

130 That reading urged our eyes to meet
131 many times, and blanched our faces;
132 but it was one moment that undid us.
